The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Calcutta University has decided to re-examine the answer scripts of all aggrieved examinees who sat for the MA (Part I) Sanskrit tests in 2005. Of the 154 examinees, 41 have failed. The results were published on Monday, eight months after the exams.

 Two persons were injured when parts of a building on Canning Street collapsed late on Tuesday. The injured were taken to a local hospital, from where they were released after first-aid. A civic official said the authorities has ordered demolition of the dilapidated portions of the building. 

 An unidentified man, in his mid-20s, died after the motorcycle he was riding was hit by a truck on BT Road, in Sodepur, on the city?s northern fringes, early on Wednesday. The truck driver fled with his vehicle.

 A car parked on the eastern slope of Bijon Setu caught fire around 9 pm on Wednesday. The fire was doused shortly by a tender. No was injured. Officials suspect an electrical short-circuit had caused the fire.

 Traffic on Beleghata Main Road was disrupted for over 20 minutes on Wednesday afternoon following a clash between two groups of autorickshaw drivers. The situation was brought under control after a contingent from Beleghata police station arrived on the spot. No one has been arrested. 

 Probir Ghosh, 58, a prominent figure in the information technology industry in the state, died on Sunday. An electronics and telecommunication engineer from Jadavpur University (1969 batch), he worked for IBM and was later a part of the team that launched PCL. He joined Globsyn Technologies in 2001. In 2005 he became its director.

